epend on differences in the nature of the opponent. The second category includes questions about the conditions for responsibility of individual soldiers and civilian officials for war crimes, and about the proper attitude of a government toward potential conscripts who reject its military policies. The third category includes disputes between absolutist, deontological, and utilitarian ethical theories, and deals with questions about the existence of insoluble moral dilemmas.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aWar (International law). 0aWarxMoral and ethical aspects. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh  aAct of state doctrine.  aAdolf Eichmann.  aAdolf Hitler.  aAggression.  aAmbiguity (law).  aAnalogy.  aAnguish.  aAnti-personnel weapon.  aAnti-social behaviour order.  aAppeasement.  aAttempt.  aBelligerent.  aCollective punishment.  aCollective responsibility.  aCombat.  aCombatant.  aCommand responsibility.  aConscientious objector.  aConscription.  aConsideration.  aCrime against peace.  aCrime.  aCrimes of War.  aCriminal code.  aCriticism.  aCruelty.  aDecision Analyst (company).  aDecision-making.  aDeclaration of war.  aDemagogue.  aDeontological ethics.  aDetermination.  aDeterrence theory.  aDirty hands.  aDistributive justice.  aEssence of Decision.  aEthical dilemma.  aEthics.  aForeign Policy.  aForeign policy.  aHostility.  aIntention (criminal law).  aInternational law.  aJust war theory.  aLaw of the United States.  aLaw of war.  aLegal burden of proof.  aMassacre.  aMilitary dictatorship.  aMilitary justice.  aMilitary necessity.  aMilitary operation.  aMilitary policy.  aMoral absolutism.  aMoral agency.  aMoral imperative.  aMoral obligation.  aMoral reasoning.  aMoral responsibility.